description: Credit to @wsj for reporting this story. It's even crazier than I could fit into the reel. Paul and Sue won their lotto 5 years to the day after their granddaughter died from Krabbe disease. They thought it was divine intervention and used half their money to fund a non-profit to help those impacted by the disease. So financial advisor John was really stealing from dying children. The allure of those commissions must have been strong.  The WSJ didn't report this, but I searched more and found John actually won several awards during this time such as "Principal Financial Group Agent of the Year" in 2013. The crazy thing to me is that everything he was doing was totally NORMAL for his type of advisor. He was pushing high-fee insurance products like many insurance salesmen do. This only got such attention because John was doing a LOT of it (churning those annuities) and buying inappropriate products for a non-profit. Had he just done a little of it, this would probably be a non-story. There's a bittersweet ending to the story. In 2020 John took his own life. Last month, in 2024, an arbitration panel awarded Principal to pay $7.3M to Paul and Sue's foundation. By my math that puts them dramatically behind where they would have been if they got good advice, but at least there's some accountability. As always, reminding you to build wealth by following the two PFC rules: 1.) Live below your means and 2.) Invest early and often. -Jeremy #lottery #lotterywinner #financialadvice #scam #principal

description: When you hear the sales pitch on permanent life insurance, it sounds almost too good to be true. That's because it is. In reality, the sales pitch contains lots of half-truths, scare tactics, and some outright lies. The truth is that insurance companies can't magically make your money grow faster than investing directly. Instead, these complex permanent life insurance policies are loaded with fees and gotchas and pay huge commissions to the salesmen who push them. Steer clear of "investing" in life insurance of any kind. If you have people who depend on your work to live (paid or unpaid), buy term life insurance for a term that covers you until they're self-sufficient. Use the rest of those premium payments to actually invest in index funds, preferably inside a tax advantated account, like an IRA or 401k.  As always, reminding you to build wealth by following the two PFC rules: 1.) Live below your means and 2.) Invest early and often. -Jeremy #lifeinsurance #iul #indexeduniversal #lifeinsuranceagent #infinitebanking #beyourownbank #mpi
